        <comment>Enemy specific behaviors.&#x0D;&#x0A;Enemy descriptions thanks to IGN: http://www.ign.com/wikis/geometry-wars-retro-evolved/Enemies</comment>
        <event-group collapsed="1" description="These lowly enemies are slow and have the IQ of cauliflower. Pinwheels are the first enemy that you&apos;ll encounter in the game and will become less and less common as your score goes up. Being hit by one kills you just the same as anything else, but they won&apos;t target you like the rest of the enemies in this game. Each Pinwheel will simply bounce off of the edges and continue along its path until you shoot it out. These fellows shouldn&apos;t be too much of a problem, even for beginners. Once things start getting hectic, you should ignore them unless they&apos;re in your path and just hope to kill them with stray fire." sid="1281524749217722" title="Pinwheel / Wanderer">
            <sub-events>
                <comment>When the enemy is created, it chooses a random direction and moves that way.</comment>
                <event-block sid="6238479924495257">
                    <conditions>
                        <condition id="-18" name="On created" sid="6315811995940015" type="Pinwheel" />
                    </conditions>
                    <actions>
                        <action behavior="EnemyMovement" id="3" name="Set angle of motion" sid="1196713285175822" type="Pinwheel">
                            <param id="0" name="Angle">random(360)</param>
                        </action>
                        <action id="0" name="Play" sid="3471291265833642" type="Audio">
                            <param id="0" name="Audio file">Enemy_spawn_orange</param>
                            <param id="2" name="Loop">0</param>
                            <param id="3" name="Volume">0</param>
                            <param id="1" name="Tag (optional)">&quot;&quot;</param>
                        </action>
                    </actions>
                </event-block>
                <comment>When the enemy hits a wall, it turns at least 90 degrees, plus a random quantity up to 90 degrees.</comment>
